      <p class="case-intro">
        Identifying high-potential international markets through search demand,
        first-party data, economic signals and localisation readiness.
      </p>

      <section>
        <h2>Overview</h2>

        <p>
          Expanding into new markets is rarely just about demand.
          It requires understanding where opportunity, consumer readiness and operational feasibility overlap.
        </p>

        <p>
          I developed a structured framework to evaluate which international markets offered
          the strongest potential for expansion. The objective was to reduce risk by combining
          search intelligence, economic signals, first-party data and localisation complexity
          into a clear strategic model.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The Challenge</h2>

        <p>
          International expansion often fails because market prioritisation is based on assumptions.
          Surface-level signals such as population size or competitor presence rarely tell the full story.
        </p>

        <p>
          The challenge was to identify markets with the strongest balance of demand,
          economic stability, localisation feasibility and existing traffic signals.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>My Approach</h2>

        <p>
          I use a structured framework to evaluate international growth opportunities,
          combining search intelligence, economic signals, first-party data and localisation
          complexity to reduce market entry risk and prioritise scalable expansion.
        </p>

        <h3>1. Market Sizing & Growth Signals</h3>
        <p>
          Analysing category demand, search trends, growth momentum and cost-efficiency
          signals across markets to identify scalable opportunities.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Economic & Demographic Validation</h3>
        <p>
          Validating market readiness by analysing GDP trends, unemployment, purchasing power
          and audience demographics.
        </p>

        <h3>3. First-party Data Validation</h3>
        <p>
          Where available, I use first-party data such as GA4 to identify whether the brand is already
          receiving traffic, engagement or conversions from specific countries, regions or cities.
          This helps validate existing demand before investing in a new market.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Industry Landscape Analysis</h3>
        <p>
          Assessing market maturity, online versus offline revenue trends, pricing stability,
          competitive density and whitespace opportunities.
        </p>

        <h3>5. Search Intent Mapping</h3>
        <p>
          Mapping branded and non-branded search demand, seasonality, local language behaviour
          and consumer terminology to align strategy with real search intent.
        </p>

        <h3>6. Go-to-Market Prioritisation</h3>
        <p>
          Ranking markets based on opportunity size, localisation effort and execution complexity,
          grouping them into quick wins, medium-effort opportunities and higher-effort bets.
        </p>
      </section>

